losely identified with both inflicting and withstanding enormous suffering, as well as with promoting and enjoying unprecedented affluence? What did Germany’s experiences of misery and abundance, fear and security, destruction and reconstruction, trauma and rehabilitation have to do with one another? How has Germany been imagined and experienced as a country uniquely stamped by pain and prosperity? The contributors to this book engage these questions by reconsidering Germany’s recent past according to the themes of pain and prosperity, focusing on such topics as welfare policy, urban history, childbirth, medicine, racism, political ideology, consumerism, and nostalgia.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aNational socialismxMoral and ethical aspects. 0aPolitical culturezGermany. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Germany.2bisacsh1 aBehrenbeck, Sabine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBetts, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBetts, Paul, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCocks, Geoffrey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEghigian, Greg, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEghigian, Greg, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFritzsche, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPence, Katherine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchenk, Ingrid M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStokes, Patricia R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080478043840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804780438423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780804780438/original  aGBV-deG